ming gently, her foot tapping the stone flags.

It was then that I turned to my silent compatriot who was ogling his broken watch.

'Ah-oo-neigh na-sheiky pah-ook,'

I said softly.

The lady's hand flew up to the nape of her neck, she turned on her heel.

'Shto?'

(what?) asked my slow-minded compatriot, glancing at me. Then he looked at the lady, grinned uncomfortably and fumbled with his watch.

'J'ai quelque chose dans le cou....

There's something on my neck, I feel it,' said Madame Lecerf.
